[Republic of China Military Police]]\n* [[People's Liberation Army Air Force]]\n* [[Political status of Taiwan]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Air force of the Republic of China}}\n{{wikisource|Air Force Uniforms Act}}\n* [http://air.mnd.gov.tw/English/ ROCAF website] \n* [http://www.mnd.gov.tw/eng/discover/aircraft.htm ROC active aircraft] {{in lang|en}}\n\n{{-}}\n{{ROC Military}}\n{{Republic of China Air Force}}\n{{air forces}}\n\n[[Category:Republic of China Air Force| ]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1920]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|text=the [[People's Liberation Army Air Force]] of the [[China|People's Republic of China]]}}\n{{other uses|Chinese Air Force (disambiguation)}}{{short description|Aviation branch of Taiwan's armed forces}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name                        = Republic of China Air Force\n| native_name                      = \u4e2d\u83ef\u6c11\u570b\u7a7a\u8ecd<br>Zh\u014dnghu\u00e1 M\u00edngu\u00f3 K\u014dngj\u016bn ([[Taiwanese Mandarin|Mandarin]])<br>Ch\u00fbng-f\u00e0 M\u00ecn-koet Khung-ki\u00fbn ([[Taiwanese Hakka|Hakka]])\n| image                            = Republic of China Air Force (ROCAF) Logo.svg\n| caption                          = \n| dates                            = \n| country                          = {{ROC}}\n| size                             = 600 aircraft\n<!-- Commanders -->\n| command_structure                =[[Ministry of National Defense (Republic of China)|Ministry of National Defense]]\n| commander1                       = Gen. Hsiung Hou-chi\n| commander1_label                 = Commanding-General\n| commander2                       = Lt. Gen. Chang Yen-ting<br>Lt. Gen. Fan Ta-wei\n| commander2_label                 = Deputy Commanding-General \n| commander3                       = Lt. Gen. Cheng Jung-feng\n| commander3_label                 = HQs' Chief of Staff \n| notable_commanders               =\n<!-- Insignia -->\n| identification_symbol            = [[File:Roundel of the Republic of China.svg|80px]] [[File:Roundel of the Republic of China \u2013 Low Visibility \u2013 Type 3.svg|80px]]\n| identification_symbol_label      = [[Military aircraft insignia|Roundel]]\n| identification_symbol_2          = [[File:Flag of the Republic of China Air Force.svg|150px]]\n| identification_symbol_2_label    = Flag\n| identification_symbol_3          = \n| identification_symbol_3_label    = \n<!-- Aircraft -->\n| aircraft_attack                  =\n| aircraft_bomber                  =\n| aircraft_electronic              = [[Northrop Grumman E-2 Hawkeye|E-2T/K]], [[Lockheed C-130 Hercules|C-130HE]]\n| aircraft_fighter                 = [[General Dynamics F-16 Fighting Falcon|F-16A/B/C/D/V Block 20/70/72]], [[Dassault Mirage 2000|Mirage-2000-5Di/Ei]], [[AIDC F-CK-1 Ching-kuo|F-CK-1A/B/C/D]], [[Northrop F-5|F-5E/F]]\n| aircraft_helicopter              = [[Sikorsky S-70|S-70C-1/1A]], [[Sikorsky S-70|S-70C-6]]\n| aircraft_helicopter_attack       =\n| aircraft_helicopter_cargo        =\n| aircraft_helicopter_multirole    =\n| aircraft_helicopter_observation  =\n| aircraft_helicopter_utility      =\n| aircraft_interceptor             =\n| aircraft_patrol                  =\n| aircraft_recon                   = RF-5E, RF-16\n| aircraft_trainer                 = [[AIDC AT-3|AT-3B]], [[T-34 Mentor|T-34]]\n| aircraft_transport               = [[Lockheed C-130 Hercules|C-130H]], [[Fokker 50]], [[Beechcraft B-1900C]], [[Boeing 737|Boeing 737-800]]\n| start_date                       = {{start date and age|1920}}\n| aircraft_helicopter_transport    =\n}}\n\nThe '''Republic of China Air Force''' ('''ROCAF'''; {{zh|t=\u4e2d\u83ef\u6c11\u570b\u7a7a\u8ecd |p=Zh\u014dnghu\u00e1 M\u00edngu\u00f3 K\u014dngj\u016bn}},) is the military [[aviation]] branch of the [[Republic of China Armed Forces]]. The ROCAF's primary mission is the defense of the airspace over and around [[Taiwan]]. Priorities of the ROCAF include the development of long range reconnaissance and surveillance networks, integrating [[C4ISTAR]] systems to increase battle effectiveness, procuring counterstrike weapons, next generation fighters, and hardening airfields and other facilities to survive a surprise attack.\n\nIn May 2005, the Ministry of National Defense indicated its intention to transfer command of all defensive missile systems to the ROCAF, while future offensive missiles would be placed under a newly formed missile command. As of 2006, all medium and long range SAM units were transferred from ROC Army's Missile Command to ROCAF, while ROCAF's airbase security units were transferred to ROC Army Military Police. However, it was revealed that in January 2011, five years of problems of integrating those long range ex-ROC Army SAM units into ROCAF has forced ROCAF high command to return those units back to ROC Army's Missile Command. Missile Command is now directly under Defense Ministry's GHQ control.\n\nIn July 2010, former United States Air Force deputy under secretary for international affairs, Bruce Lemkin, said that Taiwan's ability to defend its airspace had degraded due to its ageing fighters and that the sale of new fighter aircraft to Taiwan was an urgent priority.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://in.reuters.com/article/idINIndia-49901320100705|title=INTERVIEW - Taiwan overdue for F-16 jets, ex U.S. official say|author=Reuters Editorial|date=5 July 2010|work=Reuters India|accessdate=30 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160204145337/http://in.reuters.com/article/idINIndia-49901320100705|archive-date=4 February 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> However, the ROC Air Force has trouble getting fighter planes from abroad due to mainland China's attempts to suppress fighter sales from any country. The People's Republic of China views the island of Taiwan as a rogue province instead of an independent nation, and has called the F-16 fighter or any foreign fighter sales a \"red line.\" <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.investors.com/news/lockheed-f-16-fighter-taiwan-us-china-trade/|title=Trump Is About To Challenge China's Red Line On Taiwan|publisher=Investor's Business Daily|date=March 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/a/201809/25/WS5baa3738a310c4cc775e8073.html|title=US threatening to cross red line of bilateral ties: China Daily editorial|date=September 25, 2018|publisher=China Daily}}</ref> It is believed that mainland China plans to eliminate the ROC Air Force by preventing the sales of new aircraft whilst gradually wearing its ageing fighters into an inoperable state as they have to frequently intercept [[PLAAF]] aircraft who perform almost daily approaches to ROC airspace.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://militarywatchmagazine.com/article/china-s-plan-to-eliminate-taiwan-s-air-force-how-beijing-is-gradually-wearing-taipei-s-ageing-fighters-into-inoperability|title=China's Plan to Eliminate Taiwan's Air Force; How Beijing is Gradually Wearing Taipei's Ageing Fighters into Inoperability|publisher=Military Watch|date=June 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nationalinterest.org/blog/buzz/will-taiwan-get-new-f-16v-fighters-it-desperately-wants-67932|title=Will Taiwan Get the New F-16V Fighters It Desperately Wants?|publisher=The National Interest|date=July 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nationalinterest.org/blog/the-buzz/chinas-greatest-wish-taiwans-air-force-dying-25529|title=China's Greatest Wish: Is Taiwan's Air Force Dying?|publisher=The National Interest|date=April 24, 2018}}</ref> According to the Republic of China's defense minister, Yen Teh-fa, the People's Republic of China sends about 2,000 bomber patrols per year to the Taiwan Strait separating Taiwan and China mainland.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-taiwan-usa-china/us-says-it-is-concerned-by-chinas-attempts-to-influence-taiwan-election-idUSKBN1XW0A0 |title = U.S. Voices concern over China's attempts to sway Taiwan election|newspaper = Reuters|date = 2019-11-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://www.rand.org/content/dam/rand/pubs/research_reports/RR2500/RR2567/RAND_RR2567.pdf |title=China's Long-Range Bomber Flights: Drivers and Implications |publisher=Rand Corporation |date=2018 |accessdate= |isbn=978-1-9774-0083-3 |first1=Derek |last1=Grossman |first2=Nathan |last2=Beauchamp-Mustafaga |first3=Logan |last3=Ma |first4=Michael S. |last4=Chase}}</ref>\n\n==Organization==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=January 2020}}\nLike most of the other branches of the ROC armed forces, much of the ROCAF's structure and organization is patterned after the [[United States Air Force]]. Like the USAF, the ROCAF used to have a wing \u2192 group \u2192 squadron structure. After November 2004, tactical fighter wing switch to wing \u2192 Tactical Fighter Group, with some fighter squadrons stood down, with each tactical fighter group, still pretty much the same size as a squadron, now commanded by a full colonel.\n\n=== Republic of China Air Force Command Headquarters ===\n[[File:Air_Force_(ROCAF)_General_Hsiung_Hou-chi_\u7a7a\u8ecd\u4e0a\u5c07\u718a\u539a\u57fa_(20191129_\u7a7a\u8ecd\u53f8\u4ee4).png|thumb|right|150px|General Hsiung Hou-chi, the current Commanding-General.]]\n:Air Force GHQ is subordinate to the Chief of the General Staff (military), the Minister of National Defense (civilian) and the President.\n:*Internal Units: Personnel, Combat Readiness and Training, Logistics, Planning, Communications, Electronics & Information, General Affairs, Comptroller, Inspector General, Political Warfare.\n:*'''Air Force Combatant Command''' \n::*Weather Wing: [[Tamsui District|Tamsui]], [[New Taipei City]]\n::*Communications, Air Traffic Control & Information Wing : [[Taipei City]]\n::*Air Tactical Control Wing \n:::* Ground fixed and mobile long-range air search radar sites, consist of various TPS-117, TPS-75V, FPS-117, GE-592 and HADR radars, plus 1 [[PAVE PAWS]] (Phased Array Warning System) early warning radar site in northern Taiwan, will enter service late 2012.\n:*'''Air Defense Artillery Command''' \n::* 4 Air Defense Missile & Artillery brigades, 951st (Taipei), 952nd (Taichung), 953rd (Kaohsiung), 954th (Hualien)\n:::* 4 Air Defense Missile I-HAWK battalions, 621st, 622nd, 662nd, and 664th battalions, with Phase III and 7 Phase I batteries.\n:::* 1 TK-1/2 Air Defense Missile battalion, 951st Brigade, 611st battalion with 6 companies/batteries.\n:::* 1 Patriot PAC-2+ GEM/PAC-3 Air Defense/Anti-Ballistic Missile battalion, with 3 mixed companies/batteries that are all upgrading to PAC-3 standard, with 7 more PAC 3 companies/batteries on order.\n:::* 1 Skyguard Short Range Airbase Air Defense battalion, with 6 companies/batteries and radar sub units with OTO 35mm AAA, s\n:::* 2 Antelope Short Range Airbase Air Defense battalions, with unknown companies/batteries.\n:::* At least 2 AAA Air Defense Artillery battalions, with 40mm/L60 and 12.7mm AAA guns.\n::*Air Defense Artillery Training Center: [[Pingtung City|Pingtung]]\n::**Target Service Squadron\n::**Education Service Support Company\n::**First training company\n::**Second training company\n::**Third training company\n:*'''Education, Training & Doctrine Command'''\n\n==History==\n{{main|List of aircraft used in China before 1937|Development of Chinese Nationalist air force (1937\u20131945)}}\n[[File:Gao Zhihang.jpg|thumb|right|Air Force hero killed during the [[Second Sino-Japanese War|Second Sino-Japanese War/WWII]], fighter pilot Colonel [[Gao Zhihang]] ]]\n[[File:ROCAF.JPG|thumb|right|Retired ROCAF aircraft on permanent display at the ROC Air Force Academy]]\n\nFormally established in 1920 as the Aviation Ministry, the ROCAF was active during the tenure of the ROC on [[Mainland China]]. In this [[Warlord era|period]], various airplanes were purchased and deployed by warlords in their struggle for power until nominal [[Chinese reunification (1928)|Chinese reunification]] in 1928. In February 1932, US Reserve Lt. [[Robert McCawley Short]], who was transporting armed Chinese aircraft, shot down an IJN aircraft on February 19, 1932, and downed another on February 22 before he was killed (he was posthumously raised to the rank of colonel in the Chinese Air Service).\n\nDuring the [[Second Sino-Japanese War]] (1937\u20131945), the ROCAF participated in attacks on Japanese warships on the eastern front and along the Yangtze river including support for the [[Battle of Shanghai]] in 1937. The Chinese frontline fighter aircraft initially were mainly the Curtiss Hawk II and III and the [[Boeing P-26]] model 281, and engaged Japanese fighters in many major air battles beginning on August 14, 1937, when Imperial Japanese Navy warplanes raided [[Hangzhou Jianqiao Airport|Chienchiao airbase]]; \"814\" has thus become known as \"Air Force Day\". Chinese Boeing P-26/281 fighters engaged Japanese Mitsubishi A5M fighters in what is among the world's first aerial dogfighting between all-metal monoplane fighter aircraft. A unique mission in May 1938 saw two Chinese [[Martin B-10|B-10]] bombers fly a mission over Japan, but dropping only propaganda leaflets over the Japanese cities of [[Nagasaki, Nagasaki|Nagasaki]] and [[Saga Prefecture|Saga]], four years before 1942 [[Doolittle Raid]] on Japanese home islands. It was a war of attrition for the Chinese pilots, as many of their most experienced ace fighter pilots, such as Lieutenant [[Liu Tsui-Kang]] and Colonel [[Kao Chih-Hang]] were lost early in the war. Code breaking operations played a role in the conflict. A Japanese radio intercept unit was attached to the landing forces at Shanghai. IJN Lt. Commander Tsunezo Wachi and a Lt. Yamada, an expert in Chinese codes, enabled Japanese to make preemptive strikes against ROCAF airfields.<ref>{{cite book|last1=RADM. Layton USN|first1=Edwin T.|last2=Pineau|first2=with Roger|last3=Costello|first3=John|title=\"And I was there\" : Pearl Harbor and Midway--breaking the secrets|url=https://archive.org/details/andiwastherepear00laytrich|url-access=registration|date=1985|publisher=W. Morrow|location=New York|isbn=0-688-04883-8|pages=[https://archive.org/details/andiwastherepear00laytrich/page/47 47]|edition=1st}}</ref>\n\nIn the latter half of the Sino-Japanese War, part of [[World War II]], the ROCAF was augmented by a volunteer group of American pilots (the [[Flying Tigers]]) in 1941.<ref>{{cite web |last=Rossi |first=J.R. |url=http://www.flyingtigersavg.22web.org/tiger1.htm |title=History: The Flying Tigers - American Volunteer Group - Chinese Air Force |access-date=2012-06-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130722181853/http://www.flyingtigersavg.22web.org/tiger1.htm |archive-date=2013-07-22 |url-status=live }}</ref> Throughout the war, the ROCAF was involved in attacks on Japanese air and ground forces in the Chinese theatre.\n\nROCAF General HQ was established in June 1946. From 1946 to 1948, during the [[Chinese Civil War]], the ROCAF participated in combat against the [[People's Liberation Army]] engaging in air-to-air combat on at least eleven occasions in the areas surrounding the [[Taiwan Strait]]. The ROCAF reportedly enjoyed a 31:1 kill ratio against the PLA. GHQ was evacuated to Taiwan along with the rest of the ROC Government in April 1949 following the Communist victory in the Chinese Civil War.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/feat/archives/2016/12/04/2003660529/1|title=Taiwan in Time: The great retreat - Taipei Times|website=www.taipeitimes.com|access-date=2018-07-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180730170752/http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/feat/archives/2016/12/04/2003660529/1|archive-date=2018-07-30|url-status=live}}</ref> The ROCAF assisted in halting the PLA advance at the [[Battle of Kuningtou]] on [[Kinmen]] the same year.\n\nThe ROCAF regularly patrolled the Taiwan Straits and fought many engagements with its Communist counterpart (the [[PLAAF]]). The ROCAF received second hand equipment from the US at that time, such as the [[North American F-86 Sabre|F-86]], [[North American F-100 Super Sabre|F-100]] and [[Lockheed F-104 Starfighter|F-104]].\n\nDuring the [[Cold War]], the ROCAF was involved in combat air patrols over the Taiwan Strait and engaged the [[People's Liberation Army Air Force|PLAAF]] and PLAN-AF on several occasions. The ROCAF was also the testbed of American technology at this time. The first successful kill scored by an air-to-air missile was accomplished by a ROCAF F-86 Sabre with then experimental [[AIM-9 Sidewinder]]. ROCAF pilots also flew [[Lockheed U-2|U-2]] recon overflights of the PRC during this time with assistance from the USAF. Known as the [[Black Cat Squadron]] they flew a total of 220 missions, with 102 missions over mainland China, losing 5 aircraft. All five were shot down by [[SA-2|SA-2 surface-to-air missiles]], the same type of surface-to-air missile that shot down [[Gary Powers]] over the USSR in 1960. The 34th \"[[Black Bat Squadron]]\" flew low level missions into China as part of its mapping PRC growing air defense networks, conducting ESM and ECM missions, inserting agents behind enemy lines, and air drop resupply missions.\n[[File:C-123B in flight over US 1950s.jpg|thumb|C-123Bs in flight over US 1950s, Aircraft 641 was later transferred to Taiwan to support CIA operations]]\nStarting in November 1967, the ROC secretly operated a cargo transport detachment to assist the US and the ROV as part of [[Republic of China in the Vietnam War|its participation in the Vietnam War]]. It was based on existing formation of the 34th squadron of ROC Air force. The unit's strength included two [[C-123]] cargo aircraft, seven flight officers and two mechanics, even though a higher number of military personnel was involved through rotation. It was tasked with air transportation, airdrop and electronic reconnaissance.<ref>{{cite web |last1=TREVITHICK |first1=JOSEPH |title=America and Taiwan Had a Secret Transport Squadron in Vietnam |url=https://medium.com/war-is-boring/america-and-taiwan-had-a-secret-transport-squadron-in-vietnam-9a80b1c729cf |website=medium.com |publisher=Medium |accessdate=21 July 2019|date=2016-12-03 }}</ref> Some 25 members of the unit were killed, among them 17 pilots and co-pilots, and three aircraft were lost. Other ROC involvement in Vietnam included a secret listening station, special reconnaissance and raiding squads, military advisers and civilian airline operations (which cost a further two aircraft due to Vietnamese individually operated AA missiles).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lin |first1=Hsiao-ting |title=Taiwan's Cold War in Southeast Asia |url=https://www.wilsoncenter.org/publication/taiwans-cold-war-southeast-asia |website=/www.wilsoncenter.org |publisher=The Wilson Center |accessdate=21 July 2019|date=2016-04-07 }}</ref>\n\nFrom 1979 to 1990 the ROCAF engaged in a classified military aid program in [[Yemen Arab Republic]] known as the Great Desert Program (\u5927\u6f20\u8a08\u756b).<ref name=\"Taipei Times\" /> The program started after American President [[Jimmy Carter]] rushed 14 F-5s to the Yemeni Air Force who had no pilots or ground crew trained to operate the type or even western aircraft (they previously operated Mig-15s). The Americans and the Saudis (who were bankrolling the Yemen Arab Republic's military) requested military aid from Taiwan who provided 80 F-5 pilots, ground crews, early warning radars, and anti-aircraft missile batteries.<ref name=\"WaPo 1979\" />  All told more than a thousand ROCAF personnel deployed to Yemen.<ref name=\"Taipei Times\" />\n\nThe opposing Air Force of [[South Yemen]] was made up of [[Cuban Revolutionary Air and Air Defense Force]] pilots and maintainers with some [[Soviet]] advisors and pilots as well.<ref name=\"WaPo 1979\">{{cite news |last1=Hoagl |first1=Jim |title=Taiwanese Hired By North Yemen To Fly U.S. Jets |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1979/05/28/taiwanese-hired-by-north-yemen-to-fly-us-jets/fe051ed4-6c63-4021-93b1-1135dd3b0985/ |accessdate=21 July 2019 |agency=The Washington Post |work=The Washington Post |date=May 28, 1979}}</ref> The ROCAF force were actively involved in combat with the Cubans/Soviets and for all intents and purposes constitutes the Yemen Arab Republic's Air Force during this time. Taiwanese pilots scored a number of kills and the air-defense and early warning radar teams took casualties from aerial attacks.<ref>{{cite web |title=Northrop F-5E/F in Service with Taiwan |url=http://www.joebaugher.com/usaf_fighters/f5_31.html |website=www.joebaugher.com |publisher=joebaugher.com |accessdate=21 July 2019}}</ref> The program ended in 1990 when Saudi Arabia withdrew its diplomatic recognition of Taiwan.<ref name=\"Taipei Times\">{{cite web |last1=Jonathan Chin |first1=Lo Tien-pin and |title=Air force highlights secret North Yemen operations |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2019/01/29/2003708858 |website=www.taipeitimes.com |publisher=Taipei Times |accessdate=21 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Humanitarian operations===\nThe ROCAF has also taken part in numerous humanitarian operations. Some of the more major ones include the following:\n* [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami|Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami]], December 2004<ref name=\"asiaone.com\">{{cite web|url=http://news.asiaone.com/news/asia/taiwan-c-130-aircraft-deliver-relief-supplies-philippines|title=Taiwan C-130 aircraft deliver relief supplies to the Philippines|work=AsiaOne|accessdate=30 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160220045018/http://news.asiaone.com/news/asia/taiwan-c-130-aircraft-deliver-relief-supplies-philippines|archive-date=20 February 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>[[Humanitarian response to the 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake]]</ref>\n* [[2010 Haiti earthquake|Haiti earthquake]], January 2010<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chinapost.com.tw/taiwan/foreign-affairs/2010/02/01/243104/Air-Force.htm|title=Air Force C-130 returns after delivering supplies to Haiti|access-date=2014-09-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150501044751/http://www.chinapost.com.tw/taiwan/foreign-affairs/2010/02/01/243104/Air-Force.htm|archive-date=2015-05-01|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/americas/01/14/haiti.updates/|title=Haiti earthquake: News updates|work=cnn.com|accessdate=30 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304030208/http://edition.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/americas/01/14/haiti.updates/|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Typhoon Haiyan]], November 2013<ref name=\"asiaone.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/front/archives/2013/11/13/2003576748|title=Planes fly relief supplies to Philippines|work=taipeitimes.com|accessdate=30 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160203171718/http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/front/archives/2013/11/13/2003576748|archive-date=3 February 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Equipment and procurement==\n[[File:ROCAF E-2 take-off from Chih Hang Air Force Base 20090807.jpg|thumb|ROCAF E-2 take-off from Zhihang Air Force Base]]\n\nCurrent ROCAF inventory includes over 400 combat aircraft, the mainstays being the [[AIDC F-CK-1 Ching-kuo]] IDF (Indigenous Defense Fighter) and F-16 while the Mirage 2000-5 provides the most formidable air-defense capabilities. Older F-5 fighters are gradually being phased out but remain in service.\n\nThe United States serves as the ROCAF's main supplier of equipment and also provides training for ROCAF and [[Republic of China Navy#Aircraft|ROC Navy]] pilots at [[Luke Air Force Base|Luke AFB]] in Arizona.  This base which is between [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]] and [[Tucson, Arizona|Tucson]] has an instrumented flight area for training approximately the size of the State of Connecticut. [[German Air Force]] (Luftwaffe) and [[Marineflieger|German Naval Aviation (Marineflieger)]] who used to train at Luke AFB from 1957-1983 now train at [[NATO]] facilities at [[CFB Goose Bay]] in Canada and also alongside the [[United States Air Force|USAF]] at [[Holloman Air Force Base|Holloman AFB]] in New Mexico. As of 2019 the US Air Force is assisting the Taiwanese Air Force in sourcing new and surplus F-5 parts.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jennings |first1=Gareth |title=US seeks to restart parts manufacture for Taiwan F-5s |url=https://www.janes.com/article/88184/us-seeks-to-restart-parts-manufacture-for-taiwan-f-5s |website=janes.com |publisher=Janes |accessdate=27 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Domestic development===\n[[File:F-CK-1A 1427 Flight Demonstration in Ching Chuang Kang AFB 20140719e.jpg|thumb|left|A F-CK-1A on a demo flight]]\nPrior to 1984, ROCAF fighters were almost exclusively American-made aircraft sold under terms of a mutual defense treaty between the Republic of China and the United States. Development of the [[AIDC F-CK-1 Ching-kuo|F-CK-1 ''Ching-kuo'' Indigenous Defense Fighter (IDF)]] began in 1984 due to U.S. refusal to sell [[F-16 Fighting Falcon|F-16s]] to the ROCAF as a result of changes in national policy between the U.S. and the [[People's Republic of China]]. After a successful maiden flight in 1989, the domestically produced fighter entered service in 1994. However, the ROCAF was subsequently able to obtain F-16s from the United States as well as [[Mirage 2000-5]] fighters from France, resulting in delays to later IDF development that had been anticipated.\n\nIn response to American refusals to supply \"smart bombs\", Taiwan is developing their own equivalent of the [[Joint Direct Attack Munition]] for attacks against the PRC mainland in case of invasion preparations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.defensenews.com/article/20130921/DEFREG03/309210010/Taiwan-Develops-Smart-Munitions-Against-China-Report |title=Taiwan develops 'smart' munitions against China: report |date=21 September 2013 |website=www.defensenews.com |publisher=Agence France-Presse |accessdate=24 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[Taiwan]] is looking to replace its current fleet of [[AIDC AT-3|AT-3]] jet trainers and [[Northrop F-5|F-5]] LIFT planes with 66 advanced trainers. In 2008 the Republic of China Air Force released a request for information (RFI) and two companies including [[Lockheed Martin]] for the [[KAI T-50 Golden Eagle#Possible sales|T-50]] and [[Alenia Aermacchi]]'s [[Alenia Aermacchi M-346 Master|M-346]] responded to the request. These planes were expected to be license produced in Taiwan with a local partner firm, and the overall estimated contract value was 69 billion New Taiwan dollars (US$2.2 billion).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.storm.mg/article/57539|title=\u7a7a\u8ecd\u9ad8\u7d1a\u6559\u7df4\u6a5f\u8f49\u81ea\u88fd \u7f8e\u3001\u7fa9\u722d\u8207\u53f0\u5ee0\u5408\u4f5c\u62da690\u5104\u5546\u6a5f-\u98a8\u50b3\u5a92|access-date=2019-04-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171229185345/http://www.storm.mg/article/57539|archive-date=2017-12-29|url-status=live|date=2015-07-20}}</ref> However, after the election of President [[Tsai Ing-wen]], who intends to make Taiwan's defense industry a cornerstone for future development, it was decided to domestically design and build 66 [[AIDC XAT-5 Blue Magpie]] supersonic trainers instead of selecting the T-50 or M-346. The XT-5 with a program cost of NT$68.6 billion will be a new aircraft whose design will draw upon Taiwan's expertise gained by building the domestically produced '''Indigenous Defense Fighter'''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/front/archives/2017/02/07/2003664491 |title='Blue Magpie' program to be inked today |access-date=2019-04-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180727105943/http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/front/archives/2017/02/07/2003664491 |archive-date=2018-07-27 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 the Taiwan Air Force's Air Defense and Missile Command announced a five-year, NT$80b (US$2.54b) project to build up a full force of anti-radiation UAVs made by NCSIST.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Liao |first1=George |title=Taiwan military to spend NT$80 billion on anti-radiation drone fleet |url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3727728 |website=www.taiwannews.com.tw |publisher=Taiwan News |accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Foreign procurement===\n[[File:ROCAF C-130H 1307 Taxiing at Songshan Air Force Base 20160924.jpg|thumb|A C-130H taxiing at Songshan Air Base]]\n\nOne of the first modern jets purchased was the Northrop F-5.  In 1974 a total of 308 were purchased but, lacking spare parts, the ROC has been forced to salvage them from inoperable F-5s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/usaf-looks-to-help-taiwan-with-f-5-spares-457868/|title=The US Air Force wants to assess sources that can provide spare parts for Taiwan's fleet of Northrop F-5E fighters.|publisher=FlightGlobal|date=May 2, 2019}}</ref> Taiwan is considering reusing engines from inoperable F-5s in cruise missiles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.popularmechanics.com/military/aviation/a25736255/taiwan-reverse-engineering-fighter-jet-engines-cruise-missile/|title=Taiwan is Reverse-Engineering Fighter Jet Engines to Power a Cruise Missile|publisher=Popular Mechanics|date=January 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn February 28, 2007, the [[United States Department of Defense|US Defense Department]] approved an order made by the ROC for 218 [[AIM-120 AMRAAM|AIM-120C-7 AMRAAM missiles]], as well as 235 [[AGM-65 Maverick|AGM-65G2 Maverick missiles]], associated launchers and other equipment. The total value of this order was revealed to be US$421 million.<ref>{{cite news| url = http://hk-imail.singtao.com/news_detail.asp?we_cat=3&art_id=39235&sid=12463599&con_type=1&d_str=20070302| title = US missile deal to boost Taiwan defense| work = The Standard| date = 2007-03-02| accessdate = 2007-07-08| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070926225855/http://hk-imail.singtao.com/news_detail.asp?we_cat=3&art_id=39235&sid=12463599&con_type=1&d_str=20070302| archivedate = 2007-09-26}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2007, the [[Legislative Yuan]] also approved the upgrade of the existing PAC-2 batteries to PAC-3 standard, and, in November, the Pentagon notified the U.S. Congress of the Patriot upgrade order.<ref>{{cite web |title=Taipei Economic and Cultural Representative Office in the United States - PATRIOT Configuration 2 Ground Systems Upgrade |accessdate=2007-11-13 |url=http://www.dsca.osd.mil/PressReleases/36-b/2007/Tecro_08-10.pdf |date=2007-11-09 |publisher=[[Defense News]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071128050234/http://www.dsca.osd.mil/PressReleases/36-b/2007/Tecro_08-10.pdf |archivedate=2007-11-28 }}</ref>  On August 10, 2007, a shipment of [[Boeing Harpoon|Harpoon anti-ship missiles]], valued at an estimated $125 million, was also authorised by the U.S. Defense Department, including 60 [[Boeing Harpoon#Harpoon Block II|AGM-84L Block II missiles]] and 50 upgrade kits to bring the ROCAF's existing Harpoons up to Block II, Mark L standard.<ref>{{cite news| url = http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2007/08/10/2003373497| title = US Congress notified of possible sale of missiles| work = Taipei Times| date = 2007-08-10| accessdate = 2007-08-21| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070929133617/http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2007/08/10/2003373497| archive-date = 2007-09-29| url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nOn October 3, 2008, arms notifications were sent to Congress concerning, amongst other things, the sale of 330 PAC III missiles, 4 missile batteries, radar sets, ground stations and other equipment valued up to US$3.1 billion, the upgrade of 4 E-2T aircraft to the Hawkeye 2000 standard and US$334 million worth of spare parts for the ROCAF's F-16s, IDFs, F-5E/Fs and C-130s.<ref>{{cite web | year = 2008 | url = http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/front/archives/2008/10/05/2003425092 | title = Taiwan supporters laud weapons sale | publisher = Taipei Times | accessdate = 2009-06-20 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081006172721/http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/front/archives/2008/10/05/2003425092 | archive-date = 2008-10-06 | url-status = live }}</ref>  Late in January 2010, ROCAF received the first batch of new TC-2(V) BVR missiles ordered from CSIST, believed to have new radar seeker and improved performance from the original missile which entered service over 10 years ago.<ref name=\"The Liberty Times\">{{cite web | year = 2020 | url = https://www.libertytimes.com/2010/new/jan/28/today-p7.htm | title = ROCAF showing newly received TC-2 missiles | publisher = The Liberty Times | accessdate = 2010-01-28 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100130150556/http://www.libertytimes.com.tw/2010/new/jan/28/today-p7.htm | archive-date = 2010-01-30 | url-status = live }}</ref>  The U.S. government also announced 5 notifications to Congress for additional arms sales totaling some US$6.39 Billion, under which the ROCAF will receive 3 PAC-3 batteries with 26 launchers and 114 PAC-3 missiles.<ref>{{cite news  | url=http://www.dsca.osd.mil/PressReleases/36-b/2010/Taiwan_09-75.pdf  | title=USDA New Release  | publisher=dsca.mil  | date=2010-01-29  | accessdate=2010-01-29  | url-status=dead  | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721172014/https://www.dsca.osd.mil/PressReleases/36-b/2010/Taiwan_09-75.pdf  | archivedate=2011-07-21  }}</ref>  On February 3, 2010, ROCAF also announced at a Singapore Airshow that it had signed a new contract for 3 EC-225 SAR (Search-And-Rescue) helicopters that was awarded to Eurocopter back in December 2009 for US$111 million, along with options for 17 more EC-225s.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/feb/05/taiwanese-military-orders-german-helicopters | title=Taiwanese military orders German helicopters | publisher=The Guardian newspaper | date=2010-02-05 | accessdate=2010-02-25 | location=London | first=Tania | last=Branigan | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130909125432/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/feb/05/taiwanese-military-orders-german-helicopters | archive-date=2013-09-09 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.taiwanmilitary.org/phpBB2/viewtopic.php?t=10843 | title=Eurocopter Sale to Taiwan - Contract Detail Document | publisher=taiwanmilitary.org | date=2010-02-06 | accessdate=2010-02-25 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718110628/http://www.taiwanmilitary.org/phpBB2/viewtopic.php?t=10843 | archivedate=2011-07-18 }}</ref> On November 26, 2011, the 3 EC-225 C-SAR helicopters were loaded on board an [[Antonov An-124 Ruslan|An-124]] cargo aircraft and delivered to Chai-yi AB in Taiwan, and should enter service on July 1, 2012.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.sina.com.tw/article/20111126/5035426.html | title=EC-225 C-SAR Helo, New Military Search And Rescue Power | publisher=news.sina.com.tw | date=2011-11-26 | accessdate=2011-11-26 }}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n[[File:ROCAF F-5E 5272 Display at Chih Hang Air Force Base Apron 20130601a.jpg|thumb|left|An F-5E from the 46th Fighter aggressor squadron.]]\nOn August 31, 2010, it was announced for next year's defense budget, ROCAF's \"Medium Transport aircraft\" plan to replace 12 B-1900 VIP/transport training aircraft, believed to be 6-8+ Lockheed C-27J,  has been put on hold and might be axed, due to lack of budget, but will allocate 20+ million US dollars over next 4 years for quick runway repair.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://udn.com/NEWS/NATIONAL/NAT1/5819074.shtml | title=Next Year Defense Budget Believed To Be Lowest In 5 Years | publisher=United Daily newspaper | date=2010-08-31 | accessdate=2010-09-12 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100831113708/http://udn.com/NEWS/NATIONAL/NAT1/5819074.shtml | archive-date=2010-08-31 | url-status=live }}</ref> Other items mentioned including increases in runways from 3 to 6 at Eastern Taiwan's 3 airbases, moving 2 I-HAWK batteries to Eastern Taiwan to protect those airbases, which will double to 4 batteries, and others.<ref name=\"China Times\"/>  On November 8, 2011, a second pair of E-2T Hawkeye AEW(s/n 2501 and 2502) were loaded on a ship and sent to the US for upgrade to the E-2C 2000 standard. The first pair of E-2T (s/n 2503 and 2504) were sent to the US in June 2010 and returned to Taiwan on December 18, 2011, and will be return to service by end of the year.<ref name=\"news.chinatimes.com\">{{cite news | url=http://news.chinatimes.com/realtime/110101/112011110800835.html | title=ROCAF AEW Aircraft Loaded On Ship This Morning To Send To US For Upgrades | publisher=China Times | date=2011-11-08 | accessdate=2011-11-08 }}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://163.29.207.53/MNANew/Internet/NewsDetail.aspx?GUID=63653 | archive-url=https://archive.is/20120708174305/http://163.29.207.53/MNANew/Internet/NewsDetail.aspx?GUID=63653 | url-status=dead | archive-date=2012-07-08 | title=ROCAF AEW Hawkeye 3 project ADW Aircraft Returned, Performances Vastly Upgraded | publisher=Military News Agency | date=2011-12-18 | accessdate=2011-12-18 }}</ref>\n\nOn August 15, 2011, the United States again deferred the ROCAF request to purchase 66 new F-16C/Ds but offered a retrofit package for older F-16A/B's.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dsca.mil/PressReleases/36-b/2011/TECRO_11-39.pdf |title=Taipei Economic and Cultural Representative Office in the United States - Retrofit of F-16A/B Aircraft |publisher=DSCA |accessdate=2011-09-23 |date=2011-09-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111027051229/http://www.dsca.mil/PressReleases/36-b/2011/TECRO_11-39.pdf |archivedate=2011-10-27 }}</ref> (originally 150 were brought in 1992)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://china.usc.edu/bush-announces-sale-f-16-aircraft-taiwan-1992|title=Bush Announces Sale Of F-16 Aircraft To Taiwan, 1992|date=September 2, 1992|publisher=USC US-China Institute}}</ref> However, the US allowed the F-16A/Bs to be upgraded to the [[AN/APG-83]] radar.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web| url=http://www.janes.com/article/42231/f-16v-radar-integration-clears-way-for-taiwan-upgrade| title=F-16V Radar Integration Clears Way For Taiwan Upgrade| publisher=IHS Jane's Defence| accessdate=2014-12-15| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141023134021/http://www.janes.com/article/42231/f-16v-radar-integration-clears-way-for-taiwan-upgrade| archive-date=2014-10-23| url-status=live}}</ref> Unfortunately, it was discovered the F-16A/Bs to have rusting issue during the F-16V upgrade due to aging and Taiwan's climate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defense-aerospace.com/articles-view/release/3/198333/rust-problem-delays-delivery-of-taiwan%E2%80%99s-f_16v-jets.html|title=Rust Problem Causes Delivery Delays for Taiwan's F-16V Jets|date=December 12, 2018|publisher=Defense-Aerospace}}</ref> The $5.3 billion upgrade package for ROCAF's existing F-16A/B fighters was announced on 21 September 2011.<ref name=\"China Times\">{{cite news | url=http://news.chinatimes.com/focus/0,5243,50106489x112010090600066,00.html | title=Defending Against Second Wave Missile Attack, Quickly Fix Runways, Camouflages With Decoys | publisher=China Times | date=2010-08-31 | accessdate=2010-09-12 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100909164329/http://news.chinatimes.com/focus/0,5243,50106489x112010090600066,00.html | archivedate=2010-09-09 }}</ref> The upgrade budget was to be spread over 12 years, though the Ministry of Defense indicated that it would try to reduce the period.<ref>Liu, Nancy. [http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/library/news/taiwan/2011/taiwan-110922-cna04.htm \"F-16 A/B upgrade budget to be spread over 12 years: MND.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926150831/http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/library/news/taiwan/2011/taiwan-110922-cna04.htm |date=2011-09-26 }} ''ROC Central News Agency'', 22 September 2011.</ref> In November 2011, the [[United States-China Economic and Security Review Commission]] recommended that new fighters be sold to the ROCAF.<ref>Weisgerber, Marcus. [https://archive.is/20120724081255/http://www.defensenews.com/story.php?i=8271348&&s=TOP \"U.S. Report Recommends New Fighters for Taiwan.\"] ''Defense News'', 16 November 2011.</ref> Taiwan is also balking at the cost of the radar upgrade, as it does not want to be the lead customer who pays to develop the upgrade and also because they will be unable to afford both the upgrade and the new fighters, should these be offered.<ref>Minnick, Wendell. [http://www.defensenews.com/article/20120505/DEFREG03/305050002/Taiwan-Might-Delay-F-16-Upgrade \"Taiwan Might Delay F-16 Upgrade.\"] ''Defense News'', May 5, 2012.</ref> In response to a U.S. vote in the House of Representatives to force the sale of the C/D models, the ROC MND said that the upgrade package offered some superior capabilities over the C/D model aircraft and some defense officials have said that in light of the PRC's increasing capabilities, only the F-35 would be sufficient.<ref>Hou, Elaine. [http://focustaiwan.tw/ShowNews/WebNews_Detail.aspx?Type=aALL&ID=201205290017 \"F-35 fighters best suit Taiwan's air defense needs: official.\"] ''CNA'', 29 May 2012.</ref> In July 2012, Taiwan's Aerospace Industrial Development Corp. and Lockheed Martin announced plans to establish a maintenance and overhaul center to upgrade and maintain the F-16s in place without having to ship them back to the United States.<ref>[http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/library/news/taiwan/2012/taiwan-120712-cna01.htm \"Taiwan, U.S. companies ink MOU on F-16 upgrades.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150620144143/http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/library/news/taiwan/2012/taiwan-120712-cna01.htm |date=2015-06-20 }} ''ROC Central News Agency'', 12 July 2012.</ref> In 2012 a letter of acceptance was agreed on for a US$3.8 billion deal that included the radars, electronic warfare, structural improvements and new weapons.<ref>Hou, Elaine. [http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/library/news/taiwan/2012/taiwan-120716-cna01.htm \"Taiwan signs F-16 A/Bs upgrade deal with U.S.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150620144126/http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/library/news/taiwan/2012/taiwan-120716-cna01.htm |date=2015-06-20 }} ''ROC Central News Agency'', 16 July 2012.</ref><ref>[http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/library/news/taiwan/2012/taiwan-120719-cna01.htm \"Taiwan unlikely to acquire F-35 fighters soon: U.S. business council.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150620144130/http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/library/news/taiwan/2012/taiwan-120719-cna01.htm |date=2015-06-20 }} ''ROC Central News Agency'', 19 July 2012.</ref> A [[The Pentagon|Pentagon]] report has corroborated that claim, asserting that the PRC would probably seek to destroy ROCAF airfields in the first stages of any attack, making a STOVL fighter such as the F-35B vital for effective defense.<ref>Tkacik, John J. Jr. [http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2011/sep/20/white-house-bickering-and-taiwans-f-16s/ \"TKACIK: White House bickering and Taiwan's F-16s.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110923081010/http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2011/sep/20/white-house-bickering-and-taiwans-f-16s/ |date=2011-09-23 }} ''Wash. Times'', 20 September 2011.</ref>\n[[File:ROCAF EC-225 2251 Left Side View at Hsinchu AFB Apron 20120602.jpg|thumb|A EC225 on display at the [[Hsinchu Air Base]] open house]]\nOn April 10, 2019, Air Force Chief of Staff Liu Jen-yuan also confirmed that the Air Force is asking for a total of new-built 66 F-16V fighter jets from the U.S. to replace its aging and nearly obsolete F-5 fighters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://focustaiwan.tw/news/aipl/201904100007.aspx|title=U.S. to decide whether to grant Taiwan F-16V sale in July: MND|publisher=Focus Taiwan|date=April 10, 2019}}</ref> Previous presidents after [[George H.W. Bush]] refused to sell F-16 fighters to ROC Airforce, including former President [[George W. Bush]] in 2006 after ROC request for F-16C/Ds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defense-aerospace.com/cgi-bin/client/modele.pl?prod=73822&session=dae.23124364.1159913663.RSLgv8Oa9dUAAAYfngQ&modele=release|title=Taiwan's Plan to Buy F16C/D Suspended by U.S. President|publisher=Defense Aerospace|date=October 2, 2006}}</ref> Former President [[Barack Obama]] also refused Taiwan's request for new F-16s in 2011. The Obama administration later allowed ROC Airforce to upgrade its current F-16s though the F-16 upgrades did not start until 2017 and first upgraded aircraft were only delivered in 2018 during the Trump administration.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/19/world/asia/us-decides-against-selling-f-16s-to-taiwan.html|title=No New F-16's for Taiwan, but U.S. to Upgrade Fleet|work=The New York Times|date=September 18, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"defensenews.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.defensenews.com/air/2018/10/22/taiwan-takes-delivery-of-first-locally-upgraded-f-16/|title=Taiwan takes delivery of first locally upgraded F-16|publisher=Defense News|date=October 22, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ainonline.com/aviation-news/defense/2018-10-23/taiwan-receives-first-f-16v-upgrade|title=Taiwan Receives First F-16V Upgrade|publisher=Ainonline|date=October 23, 2018}}</ref> On August 20, 2019, the sale of F-16 C/D Block 70, also known as F-16V, are officially approved by the State Department and formally submitted to Congress.<ref name=\"cnn.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/08/20/politics/taiwan-fighter-jet-sales/index.html|title=Trump admin formally approves fighter jet sale to Taiwan amid China trade fight|publisher=CNN|date=August 20, 2019}}</ref> Per DSCA, the 66 newly built F-16s for ROC Airforce includes 75 F110 General Electric Engines and 75 AN/APG-83 Scalable Agile Beam AESA radars.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dsca.mil/major-arms-sales/taipei-economic-and-cultural-representative-office-united-states-tecro-f-16cd-block|title=Taipei Economic and Cultural Representative Office in the United States (TECRO) \u2013 F-16C/D Block 70 Aircraft and Related Equipment and Support|publisher=Defense Security Cooperation Agency|date=August 20, 2019}}</ref> The final signing of the Letter of Offer and Acceptance (LOA) for the purchase of 66 F-16V fighter jets is confirmed on December 21st, 2019. <ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3841920 | title=Taiwan and U.S. Sign agreement for F-16V figh}}</ref>\n\n== Rank and rating insignia ==\n;Officers\n{| style=\"border:1px solid #8888aa; background:#f7f8ff; padding:5px; font-size:95%; margin:0 12px 12px 0;\"\n{{Ranks and Insignia of Non NATO Air Forces/OF/Blank}}\n{{Ranks and Insignia of Non NATO Air Forces/OF/Republic of China}}\n|}\n\n;Enlisted\n{| style=\"border:1px solid #8888aa; background:#f7f8ff; padding:5px; font-size:95%; margin:0 12px 12px 0;\"\n{{Ranks and Insignia of Non NATO Air Forces/OR/Blank}}\n{{Ranks and Insignia of Non NATO Air Forces/OR/Republic of China}}\n|}\n\n\n=== Current inventory ===\n[[File:ROCAF F-16A 6623 Flight Demonstration in Ching Chuang Kang Air Force Base 20161126a.jpg|thumb| A ROCAF F-16A on a demonstration flight]]\n[[File:ROCAF Sikorsky S-70C-1A Bluehawk Aoki-4.jpg |thumb|A [[Sikorsky UH-60 Black Hawk#Taiwan (Republic of China)| S-70C-1A Bluehawk]] fly over at the [[Hsinchu Air Base]] open house]]\n[[File:ROCAF Boeing 737-800 in Songshan Air Force Base 20111225.JPG|thumb|[[Boeing 737-800]] [[Air transports of heads of state and government#Taiwan|Presidential Jet]] at [[Songshan Airport]]]]\n\n{| class = \"wikitable\"\n! style = \"text-align:center; background:#acc;\"|Aircraft\n! style = \"text-align: center; background:#acc;\"|Origin\n! style = \"text-align:l center; background:#acc;\"|Type\n!